title: NASA's InSight Waits Out Dust Storm
summary: InSight’s team is taking steps to help the solar-powered lander continue operating for as long as possible.

title: Rocket Lab set to launch “It Argos Up From Here” mission
summary: Rocket Lab is set to launch its 31st Electron rocket on the “It Argos Up From Here” mission, which will launch from Rocket Lab’s private Launch Complex 1B (LC-1B), on the Mahia Peninsula in New Zealand. Liftoff is currently scheduled for Saturday, Oct. 8 at 6:09 AM NZT (17:09 UTC on Oct. 7).

title: Ariane 6 upper stage testing underway
summary: ArianeGroup has started static-fire tests of the upper stage of the Ariane 6 rocket, a key step in the development of the vehicle whose first launch remains uncertain.

title: Rocket Report: Falcon Heavy launch on tap; South Korea seeks Russia alternative
summary: Also, the Ariane 6 rocket is inching closer to the launch pad.

title: AFRL developing ‘cyber range’ for space operators
summary: AFRL is developing a cyber training range where Space Force operators could practice defending satellites using actual spacecraft in orbit

title: India on track for OneWeb launch in second half of October
summary: India expects to conduct the first launch of OneWeb satellites in eight months during the second half of October, Indian space agency ISRO said Oct. 5.

title: York Space wins $200 million Space Development Agency contract for 12 satellites
summary: York Space won a $200 million contract for the Space Development Agency's Tranche 1 Demonstration and Experimentation System (T1DES) program

title: SpaceX launch with Intelsat Galaxy sats now set for Friday
summary: SpaceX was set to launch Intelsat’s Galaxy 33 (G-33) and Galaxy 34 (G-34) satellites on Thursday, Oct. 6, from Space Launch Complex 40 (SLC-40) at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida. However, an auto-abort by Falcon 9 at T-30 seconds stopped the count for the day.

title: Dual satellite launch for Intelsat next on SpaceX’s launch schedule
summary: For the third time in 31 hours, SpaceX is poised to fire a Falcon 9 rocket into space Thursday, this time on a mission from Cape Canaveral with two commercial Intelsat television broadcasting satellites heading for geostationary orbit that are part of a multibillion-dollar program to clear C-band frequencies for 5G wireless services.

title: UK competition watchdog has concerns about Viasat’s Inmarsat takeover
summary: Viasat’s $7.3 billion Inmarsat takeover could lead to more expensive and poorer quality Wi-Fi for plane passengers, the U.K.’s competition watchdog said Oct. 6 as it prepared to launch a full-scale probe of the deal.
